 loan money with interest, Jews financed building projects, provided loans to students, and bought and rented out housing. Historical texts show that they shared meals and beer, celebrated at weddings, and sometimes even ended up in bed with Christians.Yet Church authorities feared the consequences of Jewish contact with Christians and tried to limit it, though to little avail. Royal protection also proved to be a double-edged sword: when revolts broke out against the unpopular king Henry III, some of the rebels, in debt to Jewish creditors, killed Jews and destroyed loan records. Vicious rumors circulated that Jews secretly plotted against Christians and crucified Christian children. All of these factors led Edward I to expel the Jews from England in 1290. Paradoxically, Tolan shows, thirteenth-century England was both the theatre of fruitful interreligious exchange and a crucible of European antisemitism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewszEnglandxHistoryyExpulsion, 1290. 0aJewszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewszGreat BritainxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Norman Conquest to Late Medieval (1066-1485).2bisacsh  a1290.  aAntisemitism.  aEdward I.  aHenry III.  aIsaac of Norwich.  aJewish History.  aJews in England.  aMedieval England.  aPersecution of minorities.  aSimon de Montfort.  abadges.  ablood libel.  acreditors.  aexpulsion.  afinance.  afraternization.  aintegration.  aking of England.  amoney lending.  apapal bull.  aprosperity.  aroyal privilege.  atax taxation.  athirteenth century.  ausury.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook p